{
  "texts": [
    "A critical aspect is the robot's ability to halt or recover from unsafe tasks [9], ensuring actions remain within predefined safety limits [12].Despite advancements in robotic control and artificial intelligence, service robots face persistent challenges in real-time validation, contextual knowledge representation, and logical reasoning [13].",
    "These limitations hinder their safe and efficient operation in dynamic environments, limiting real-world adoption [14].",
    "For example, misidentifying object properties (e.g., weight or fragility) can lead to unsafe actions, such as dropping objects or applying incorrect force [15], [16].",
    "Addressing these challenges is essential for reliable human-robot collaboration [17], [18].To enhance safety, approaches leveraging Large Language Models (LLMs) [19], [20] and Knowledge Graphs (KGs) [21], [22] have been explored.",
    "LLMs enable robots to interpret human instructions and generate task plans but lack real-time environmental awareness [23], [24]."
  ]
}